    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.23.27-28_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">27</fw>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">WISCONSIN STATE COLLEGE
                        <lb/>
                    WHITEWATER</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        8-30-55
                        235 <hi rend="caps">N.</hi> Graham Ave.
                        Whitewater
                    </dateline>
               
                    <salute>Dear Dr. Neihardt-</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Despite time and distance, you seem at the moment quite near &#8212; so near that silence would be discourteous. But you have really <unclear>never been</unclear> very far away since our hours together last summer. Perhaps the heat branded <del>them</del> me with them. And I have yearned this month to roar across the plains to see you again. But my whip said no &#8212; not earned. Still, I have watched the weather and pretended &#8212; and rejoiced in Missouri rains. ...</p>
                
                <p>Last fall I made you a vow that I would get the first section of my <del>thesi</del> dissertation on paper before the year-end. Literally I kept it, but not as I had intended. At Christmastime I read the shoddy thing and destroyed it. It was dull, incoherent, unenlightening. Yesterday after a month's lashing, I finished the rough draft of Stage I, first part &#8212; and analysis of <hi rend="underline">The Divine Enchantment</hi>. Today I begin the second part, which will be biographical sketch with attachment to <hi rend="underline"><hi rend="caps">D. E.</hi></hi> Stage II, the Lyricist, will probably review the procedure, doing the biographical section first and the critical second. Stage III, the Epic Poet, is not yet taking shape in my mind. But at last I have gained some momentum &#8212; and have promised Emma not to destroy <del/> any portion <del>without</del> before replacing it.</p>
                
                <p>Of course there is the ominous certainty of over four hundred freshmen straining facilities and faculty next week &#8212; the student load will be heavier than ever. But at the moment I am not too much concerned &#8212; I am much more curious about <del/> whether the <del>curious</del> unorthodox organization of my paper can be made to work&#8212; and whether it can contribute anything in addition to my <unclear>scrapings</unclear> from the collection (<hi rend="caps">U.</hi> Mo.) and elsewhere.</p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.23.27-28_0002"/>
                
                <p>So this has been a pleasant month &#8212; except for that yearning! I sent Emma and the kids to visit in Pennsylvania and Connecticut for three weeks so that I could get started. But I was glad when they returned &#8212; wrote about as much in the ten days after they got back as I had in the preceding twenty! All are well and vigorous, though subdued ("Pappy is working!").</p>
                
                <p>I hope that "All is [still] well" with you and yours. My affection to the whole household&#8212;</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Yours,</salute>
                    <signed>Paul</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></opener> <p>Was <hi rend="caps"><hi rend="underline">D.E.</hi></hi> written in the same order as it was published?</p>
                    
                    <p>Has more of your reading been recorded ?</p>
                    
                    <p>What is the formal name of the <hi rend="caps">MS</hi> custodian who was so helpful to me last summer?</p>
                    <milestone unit="section"/><ab>----</ab>
                    <p>no rush on these questions.</p>
                </postscript>
                
                <note type="curatorial"><hi rend="caps">JOHN G. NEIHARDT CENTER</hi></note>
                
            </div1>
            
            
